reference_review:
SUMMARY:
Thank you for the latest cleanups. They made the code much easier to understand.
Reading the code again I see that, if I am not mistaken, it breaks the existing (implicit) contract for the cache image data, such that it would like lead to a regression. That's why I request changes to avoid that we break existing behavior,
In addition, all the changes related to creating a temporary handle based on zoom for executing a drawing operation on look far more complicated than they need to be to me. I wrote a longer comment trying to explain what in my opinion can/should be done to improve that.

POINTS:
- [bundles/org.eclipse.swt/Eclipse SWT/common/org/eclipse/swt/graphics/ImageDataAtSizeProvider.java:20] This methods needs a Javadoc. And I propose to simplify the parameter names.
```suggestion
	ImageData getImageData(int width, int height);
```
- [bundles/org.eclipse.swt/Eclipse SWT/common/org/eclipse/swt/graphics/ImageDataAtSizeProvider.java:25] This interface needs a Javadoc.
- [bundles/org.eclipse.swt/Eclipse SWT/gtk/org/eclipse/swt/graphics/Image.java:1589] Can't we just call this `drawAtSize` and also simplify the parameters accordingly? I don't see that we need the existing width/height parameters, as their values just seem to be imageData.width/height.
```suggestion
public static void drawAtSize(GC gc, ImageData imageData, int width, int height) {
```
- [bundles/org.eclipse.swt/Eclipse SWT/win32/org/eclipse/swt/graphics/Image.java:828] Is the `WithZoomFallback` extension necessary/relevant? For the consumer, it shouldn't matter if the handle is created with based on zoom or anything else, should it?
```suggestion
void executeOnImageHandleAtSize(HandleAtSizeConsumer handleAtSizeConsumer, int targetWidth,
```
- [bundles/org.eclipse.swt/Eclipse SWT/win32/org/eclipse/swt/graphics/Image.java:2083] Passing `scaled == false` will lead to entries in `cachedImageData` that are incompatible with the current contract of that cache. The cache is supposed to contain the appropriate image data for a given zoom and not randomly some unscaled or different scaled image data. I would expect this to likely/eventually break.
At the same time I do not understand all the complexity with `getImageDataUnscaled`, the extension of `newImageData()` with the `scaled` parameter and transitive effects. All this is only used seems to be used in `loadImageDataClosestTo`. Why not just check if the handle map already contains an appropriate handle for that case and, if not, create one with the exact required code, which should effectly only be the simplified implementation of `initializeHandleFromSource()` (i.e., the one without scaling), shouldn' it? So something like:
```java
  private ImageData loadImageDataClosestTo(int targetWidth, int targetHeight) {
    ...
    initializeUnscaledHandle(zoomContext)
  }

  private ImageHandle initializeUnscaledHandle(ZoomContext zoomContext) {
    ElementAtZoom<ImageData> imageDataAtZoom = loadImageData(zoomContext.targetZoom());
    ImageData imageData = imageDataAtZoom.element();
    imageData = adaptImageDataIfDisabledOrGray(imageData);
    ImageHandle handle = newImageHandle(imageData, zoomContext);
    ImageData result = handle.getImageData();
    handle.destroy();
    return imageData
}
```

When doing that cleanup, it turns out that this flow creates a temporary handle just for the sake of creating the appropriate image data but to then later on to create another temporary handle to execute an operation on. So we create two handles even though we only need one. It seems reasonable to me to combine these to cases, i.e., in case we need to create a temporary handle based on zoom for executing the drawing operation on, to just create a handle as in the above proposed `initializeUnscaledHandle` method and directly use that one to execute the drawing operation.

